  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Helps track potential money laundering activities\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal crime\n- Establishes penalties for individuals and organizations involved in laundering money\n\n3. The Anti-Money Laundering Act (AMLA) of 2020\n- Modernizes and strengthens existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhances reporting requirements and penalties\n\n4. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Expanded regulations to combat money laundering\n- Increased reporting and compliance requirements for financial institutions\n- Strengthened measures to prevent terrorist financing\n\n5. The Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act\n- Requires reporting of large currency transactions\n- Helps prevent money laundering and tax evasion\n\nThese federal statutes provide legal frameworks for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
